  "summary": "Inspector Taverner informs Brenda Leonidis that her husband, Aristide, died from icodrine poisoning after someone deliberately switched his insulin for eye drops. Brenda denies involvement, claiming she only administered his usual dose before rushing to find Roger, and she suggests a servant might be responsible.\n\nTaverner, accompanied by the narrator, the Chief Constable, and Detective Inspector Lamb, moves to a room overlooking the garden to interview Lawrence Brown, a tutor who had been studying Latin with the student, Eustace. Upon their arrival, Lawrence appears visibly terrified. During the encounter, Eustace leaves the room after making a slicing motion across his throat toward the narrator. When Taverner suggests a possible motive involving a romantic relationship between Lawrence and Brenda, Lawrence vehemently denies any affair or murderous intent, citing his religious beliefs and sensitive nature, before fleeing the room in distress.\n\nFollowing the interview, the investigators discuss potential suspects. Detective Inspector Lamb suggests the crime could be an act of euthanasia or a way for Lawrence to marry into Brenda's wealth, which includes significant assets and sapphires. Taverner expresses suspicion toward Brenda, noting her failure to dispose of the insulin bottle, though he acknowledges a lack of concrete evidence. He also notes a housekeeper's observation that the couple seemed close.\n\nThe narrator returns to Brenda to gather impressions. Brenda expresses intense resentment toward the family, calling them \"beasts\" and claiming they were mean to her, but she defends her love for her husband, stating she loved him very much despite his age.",
